  "introduction": "Imagine you have two bottles: one contains Ethanol (found in hand sanitizer) and the other contains Phenol. Both contain an -OH group! If I drop a piece of sodium metal into both, they react differently. Why? The answer lies not just in the OH group, but in what that carbon atom is attached to. Today, we unlock this structural secret.",
  "theory": {
    "overview": "This session introduces the fundamental classification of oxygen-containing organic compounds: Alcohols and Phenols. We focus on the IUPAC definitions and the critical distinction between aliphatic (sp3) and aromatic (sp2) carbon attachment for the hydroxyl group.",
    "keyPoints": [
      "Alcohols have -OH attached to sp3 hybridized carbons of an alkyl chain.",
      "Phenols have -OH attached directly to sp2 hybridized carbons of a benzene ring.",
      "Classification (1°, 2°, 3°) depends on the number of carbon atoms bonded to the C-OH carbon."
    ],
    "detailedContent": "Alcohols are derived from aliphatic hydrocarbons. The general formula is R-OH, where R represents an alkyl group. The carbon atom bearing the -OH group is sp3 hybridized (tetrahedral geometry). Examples include Methanol and Ethanol.\n\nPhenols are a distinct class derived from aromatic compounds like benzene. In phenol, the -OH group is attached directly to the benzene ring. The carbon atom involved in this bond is part of the aromatic system and is sp2 hybridized (trigonal planar geometry). This structural difference leads to significant differences in chemical properties which we will explore later.\n\nClassification: Alcohols are classified based on the number of alkyl groups attached to the carbon bearing the -OH group. If one, it's primary; two, secondary; three, tertiary."
  },
